            <fr:title text="Shared memory (GPU)">Shared memory (GPU)</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><html:p><html:em>Shared memory</html:em> on a GPU is a small (per-block) on-chip scratchpad with latency comparable to L1. Software-managed — the programmer explicitly stages data through it, the hardware does not cache for them. Used to:</html:p><html:ul><html:li>Avoid non-coalesced global accesses by reorganizing data layouts on the fly.</html:li>
  <html:li>Reuse loaded data across threads within a block.</html:li>
  <html:li>Communicate between threads within a block.</html:li></html:ul><fr:tree show-metadata="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/kellenkanarios/" title="Kellen Kanarios" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/kellenkanarios/" display-uri="kellenkanarios" type="local">Kellen Kanarios</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2026</fr:year><fr:month>5</fr:month><fr:day>25</fr:day></fr:date><fr:uri>https://kellenkanarios.com/OGCRU/</fr:uri><fr:display-uri>OGCRU</fr:display-uri><fr:route>/OGCRU/</fr:route><fr:title text="Bank conflicts (GPU)">Bank conflicts (GPU)</fr:title></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><html:p>Shared memory is divided into <html:em>banks</html:em> (typically 32). Each bank can service one access per cycle. If two threads in a <fr:link href="/X9VZ/" title="Warp scheduling" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/X9VZ/" display-uri="X9VZ" type="local">Warp scheduling</fr:link> access different addresses in the <html:em>same</html:em> bank, the accesses serialize — a <html:em>bank conflict</html:em>.</html:p><html:p>Three behaviors when warp threads access shared memory:</html:p><html:ul><html:li>Different banks: full parallelism. No conflict.</html:li>
  <html:li>Same bank, same word: hardware broadcasts the word to all threads. No conflict.</html:li>
  <html:li>Same bank, different words: serialize.</html:li></html:ul>
    <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/kellenkanarios/" title="Kellen Kanarios" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/kellenkanarios/" display-uri="kellenkanarios" type="local">Kellen Kanarios</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2026</fr:year><fr:month>5</fr:month><fr:day>25</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>Question</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>How to avoid bank conflicts?</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>

    <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/kellenkanarios/" title="Kellen Kanarios" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/kellenkanarios/" display-uri="kellenkanarios" type="local">Kellen Kanarios</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2026</fr:year><fr:month>5</fr:month><fr:day>25</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>Answer</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>Change the access pattern so threads hit different banks (often by transposing or by adding padding to break the stride that causes the conflict).</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
    <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors /><fr:date><fr:year>2026</fr:year><fr:month>5</fr:month><fr:day>12</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>Remark</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>The GPU memory hierarchy is software-managed at L1 (shared memory) and coherent only at L2 — by restricting L1 to local-to-block scope, the architecture sidesteps the cost of a global <fr:link href="/GA7N/" title="Cache coherence" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/GA7N/" display-uri="GA7N" type="local">Cache coherence</fr:link> protocol on a thousand-way-parallel chip.</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
<fr:tree show-metadata="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors /><fr:date><fr:year>2026</fr:year><fr:month>5</fr:month><fr:day>12</fr:day></fr:date><fr:uri>https://kellenkanarios.com/U1FO/</fr:uri><fr:display-uri>U1FO</fr:display-uri><fr:route>/U1FO/</fr:route><fr:title text="Memory coalescing">Memory coalescing</fr:title></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><html:p>The hardware optimization on GPUs that combines simultaneous memory accesses by threads in a <fr:link href="/X9VZ/" title="Warp scheduling" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/X9VZ/" display-uri="X9VZ" type="local">Warp scheduling</fr:link> into a single transaction — when the accessed addresses fall in the same cache line.</html:p><html:p>Global memory latency on a GPU is 400–800 cycles. Coalescing is the primary way to keep the SM fed:</html:p><html:ul><html:li>If all 32 threads in a warp access addresses within one cache line: one memory transaction, full bandwidth.</html:li>
  <html:li>If addresses span multiple cache lines: the hardware serializes into multiple transactions; bandwidth drops proportionally.</html:li></html:ul>
    <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors /><fr:date><fr:year>2026</fr:year><fr:month>5</fr:month><fr:day>12</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>Remark</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>Address permutations within a cache line don't hurt utilization — coalescing is about which lines are touched, not which exact bytes.</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
<html:p>Coalescing is why memory layout matters so much for GPU code. The standard idiom is <html:em>structure-of-arrays</html:em> (SoA) instead of <html:em>array-of-structures</html:em> (AoS): threads accessing the same field of consecutive records hit consecutive bytes, which coalesce; threads accessing the same struct don't.</html:p>
    <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors /><fr:date><fr:year>2026</fr:year><fr:month>5</fr:month><fr:day>12</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>Question</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>Should you always cache on the GPU?</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>

    <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors /><fr:date><fr:year>2026</fr:year><fr:month>5</fr:month><fr:day>12</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>Answer</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>No. If you're memory-bound and have no <fr:link href="/PMP9/" title="Spatial locality" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/PMP9/" display-uri="PMP9" type="local">Spatial locality</fr:link>, cache is wasted on data you won't reuse. CUDA exposes the option to disable L1 caching for these cases, which lets misaligned loads transfer only the bytes needed instead of full cache lines.</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree></fr:mainmatter>
